ountries so far. "If we look at the developed countries, only 8 percent who do not have access to finance, while in developing countries 59 percent," said Destry.\r\n\r\n"There should be measures to increase awareness of all stakeholders to create a range of up to a small community bank," said Destry.\r\n\r\nIn 2012, Destry continued penetration of Indonesian banks have declined by 41 percent. In fact, in the previous year to reach 43 percent.\r\n\r\nMeanwhile, on the credit side is still in the range of approximately 35 percent of gross domestic product (GDP). This figure is much smaller than Malaysia which has reached 100 percent.\r\n\r\n"Limited access to finance of Indonesian society is in need of serious attention from the stakeholders. Awareness We will try to open the banking sector to work together to improve the community in order to increase financial awareness of inclusive growth," he said.\r\nDifficulty of access\r\nSeeing this fact, according to Destry, several factors constrain the Indonesian financial sector, among others, lack of awareness and access to transactions, savings, credit, and insurance. "Our financial sector is enormous room for growth, it should be developed further," said Destry.\r\n\r\nDeputy Governor of Bank Indonesia (BI), Halim Alam, never alludes to the fundamental problems faced by micro, small, and medium enterprises (SMEs) is access to capital. Based on BI data, earning outstanding credit in the SME sector by April 2013 reached Rp570 trillion or 19.6 percent of total bank credit.\r\n\r\nTo overcome this, Halim said the central bank had asked banks willingness to lend to SMEs by 20 percent sequentially. Lending is expected to be a driver of higher economic growth.\r\n\r\n"We know not all banks are experts in SME lending, for that we recommend to gradual or cooperation with financial institutions with expertise in SME lending," Halim said some time ago in Jakarta.\r\n\r\nThe central bank will also strengthen policies related to inclusive financial sector and micro, small, and medium enterprises (SMEs). BI Governor Agus Martowardojo, Thursday, November 14, 2013, stating that this policy plays a role in encouraging intermediation and banking efficiency.\r\n\r\nAccording to Agus, this policy will also contribute to strengthening the stability of the financial system and support the policies in the field of payment systems. "Inclusive financial policy is focused on five strategies," Agus said in Jakarta.\r\n\r\nFive strategies it is strengthening financial education, increased access, consumer protection, the provision of information, and the stability of the financial system as well as setting policy recommendations to the relevant authorities. (Vivanews.com)', 'Towards a People\'s Blueprint "Literacy" Financial Services', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '438-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-12 10:58:49', '2014-06-12 03:58:49', '', 438, 'http://localhost/perbanas/en/438-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(440, 1, '2013-12-19 11:00:59', '2013-12-19 04:00:59', 'Jakarta – The rapid development of technology in the information and communication sector, as well as globalization in the banking system, has made banks become main targets for money laundering. This is due to the fact that banks still play a strategic role in supporting the financial system in Indonesia.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nAlso, the strict confidentiality of banks is also one of the main considerations for money launderers.\r\n\r\nThus conveyed by banking law analyst, Pradjoto, in a seminar held by the Indonesia Banks Association (PERBANAS) themed “Legal Review on the Role of Banks in Indonesia in Facing Money Laundering and Terrorism Funding”, held in Jakarta, Thursday, 19 December 2013.\r\n\r\nAccording to Pradjoto, it is important to apply the principles of Know Your Customer (KYC) in every bank transaction. Also, there needs to be strong supervision and commitment from the banking board of directors and commissioners, as well as reports to the Financial Transaction Report and Analysis Center (PPATK), should there be any suspicious transactions.\r\n\r\nHead of PERBANAS Law Sector who is also Director of Compliance, Corporate Affairs &amp; Legal at PT Bank CIMB Niaga Tbk, L. Wulan Tumbaleka says, money laundering can now be done by anyone from all levels of society. The techniques used are also more advanced, therefore seeming more competitive with the eradication efforts done by law enforcers.\r\n\r\n“Perbanas calls for the banking society as well as the general public to share their experiences and play an active role in overseeing financial transactions which can potentially be crimes of money laundering or terrorism funding,” says Wulan.\r\n\r\nAs an organization for national banks in Indonesia, Perbanas, through its Law Sector, has given recommendations to the government in the drafting of Banking Laws, recommendations in general as well as specifically concerning money laundering. Direct recommendations from banking practitioners in Indonesia are important to achieve a Banking Law which is appropriate with the needs of the banking industry as well as stakeholders.\r\n\r\nAccording to Wulan, recommendations from Perbanas are based on proposals and ideas from national banks. “Recommendations from Perbanas for the Banking Law have become a commitment for Perbanas in order to achieve a better future for the banking industry,” closed Wulan. (infobanknews.com)\r\n\r\nAs an organization that embodies national banks in Indonesia, Perbanas, through Perbanas Legal Affairs, has provided input to the government in the preparation of the Act (the Act) Banking, both in general and with regard to the crime of money laundering. Direct input from the banking industry in Indonesia, it becomes important for the creation of the Banking Law that really fit the needs of the banking industry and stakeholders.\r\n\r\nInputs given Perbanas, according Wulan, or have previously been proposed based on the idea of ​​national banks. "Inputs from Perbanas to be committed Perbanas Banking Act in order to bring the future of the banking industry better," Wulan lid. (Infobanknews.com)', 'Banks an Easy Target for Money Laundering', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'banks-so-soft-targets-money-laundering-offenders', '', '', '2014-06-24 08:00:32', '2014-06-24 01:00:32', '', 0, 'http://localhost/perbanas/en/?post_type=news&#038;p=440', 0, 'news', '', 0),
