(1092, 1, '2014-06-23 09:38:09', '2014-06-23 02:38:09', 'Jakarta – President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono (SBY), Tuesday 19 November 2013, officially launched the blueprint for “Indonesian Banking Literacy”. The President says this guide will be a reference in increasing the knowledge of financial stakeholders.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThis guide is also hoped to become a literacy movement which will create a more literate society towards financial services. “A large part of our society lives outside or on the outskirts of these financial services, therefore let’s bring them in,” said SBY in his speech at the launching in Jakarta.\r\n\r\nThis national strategy is a process or series of activities aimed to increase the trust of consumers and the general public so they can manage their finances better.\r\n\r\nThe President hopes that the Financial Services Authority (FSA) can synergize with stakeholders so that this national strategy can be achieved on target. “Cooperate with Governors and Regents, involve all stakeholders,” says SBY.\r\n\r\nThree problems\r\n\r\nThe Head Commissioner of FSA, Muliaman D. Hadad also adds that this blueprint consists of three main pillars. First is education and financial literacy campaigns. “This activity targets stay at home moms and all other elements of society,” says Muliaman.\r\n\r\nSecond is strengthening the financial literacy infrastructure. In this case the FSA has provided a website and literacy car which will be distributed to every province to educate society.\r\n\r\nThird is the development of financial literacy products and services. This is done by providing financial products and services to the public. “At the moment many are within reach, among others Micro Insurance with an affordable policy,” says Muliaman.\r\n\r\nAt another event, Coordinating Minister for Economic Affairs Hatta Rajasa, Tuesday 19 November 2013, welcomes the launch of Indonesian Financial Literacy, keeping in mind the fact that the Indonesian society still has little understanding on financial access.\r\n\r\nAccording to Hatta, based on reports and previous observations, society’s understanding specifically those of the productive age towards financial access is still around 40 percent. The rest are still blind on this matter. This means that around 60 percent of our productive society is still unable to utilize financial services.\r\n\r\n“That is where the role of FSA is important,” comments Hatta to VIVAnews.\r\n\r\nThis shows that there has been a problem with the public’s understanding towards financial products and services, therefore making them unenthusiastic towards various products such as financing facilities as well as loans and credits provided by banks and other financial services.\r\n\r\nHatta suggests that society prefers to save money and collect money to fulfill their needs rather than receive bank loans.\r\n\r\nMany banks offer financing products as well as business facilities, especially those aimed at small and medium businesses. However, not many capital credits have been utilized by small and medium businesses.\r\n\r\n“Credit is not just debt. You can save money, pay easily, and run a business,” says Hatta.\r\n\r\nTherefore, Hatta is optimistic that this guide to Indonesian Financial Literacy will increase society’s access to financial products and services in Indonesia.\r\n\r\nEconomist at PT Bank Mandiri Tbk, Destry Damayanti concludes that the rapid development of Indonesia’s banking industry is not in line with easy access to banking services. This condition causes Indonesia’s financial sector to experience limitations in reaching lower class society.\r\n\r\nAccording to Destry, currently only 20 percent of Indonesia’s citizens aged 15 have access to the financial sector. Not only that, from the total of 230 million citizens in Indonesia, only around 2 million or less than 1 percent of the total population has access to the capital market.\r\n\r\nThe comparison to developed countries is astounding. “If we see developed countries, only 8 percent of the population does not have financial access, however in developing countries it is 59 percent,” states Destry.\r\n\r\n“There needs to be an effort to increase stakeholders’ awareness in providing banking access to lower class society,” says Destry.\r\n\r\nIn 2012, Destry continues, banking penetration in Indonesia decreased by 41 percent, whereas in the previous year it reached 43 percent.\r\n\r\nAs for credit distribution, the number is around 35 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP). This number is way below that of Malaysia which has reached 100 percent.\r\n\r\n“Limited financial access for the Indonesian society needs to be taken seriously by stakeholders. We will try to increase the awareness of banks to cooperate in an effort to increase society’s financial awareness,” she says.\r\n\r\nLimited access\r\n\r\nSeeing the facts, according to Destry, several factors which remain to be obstacles in Indonesia’s financial sector are among others, society’s limited awareness and access towards transactions, savings, credit, and insurance. “Our financial sector has a big opportunity to grow, we should develop it more,” says Destry.\r\n\r\nDeputy Governor of Bank Indonesia (BI), Halim Alamsyah, mentioned that the basic problem faced by micro, small and medium businesses (UMKM) is capital access. Based on BI data, outstanding productive credit in the UMKM sector as per April 2013 has only reached Rp 570 trillion or 19.6 percent from total banking credits.\r\n\r\nAs a solution, adds Halim, BI has asked banks to provide credits for UMKM up to 20 percent cumulatively. The credit given is hoped to be able to support an increase in economic growth.\r\n\r\n“We know not all banks are experts in providing credit to UMKM, for that matter we suggest a cumulative approach or form cooperation with financial institutions who are more experienced,” says Halim.\r\n\r\nThe Central Bank will also reinforce regulations concerning inclusive finance and UMKM. BI Governor, Agus Martowadojo, Thursday 14 November 2013, explains that the regulations will play a role in encouraging banking intermediation and efficiency.\r\n\r\nAccording to Agus, the regulations will also contribute in strengthening the stability of the financial system and support regulations in the payment system sector. “The inclusive finance regulations will be focused on five strategies,” said Agus in Jakarta.\r\n\r\nThe five strategies are improving financial education, increasing access, consumer protection, providing information, and regulating the stability of the financial system as well as regulatory recommendations for related authorities. (vivanews.com)', 'Blueprint Towards a ‘Financial Literate’ Society', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '438-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-06-23 09:38:09', '2014-06-23 02:38:09', '', 438, 'http://localhost/perbanas/en/438-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
